data.chText: （把衣服、纸张等的边缘）塞进，折叠，卷起
data.enText: to push, fold or turn the ends or edges of clothes, paper, etc. so that they are held in place or look neat

data.chText: 她撩起裙子蹚水走进河里。
data.enText: She tucked up her skirt and waded into the river.

data.chText: 床单的四边应整整齐齐地掖在褥垫下面。
data.enText: The sheets should be tucked in neatly (= around the bed) .

data.chText: 把信封的口盖塞进信封里。
data.enText: Tuck the flap of the envelope in.

data.chText: 把…塞进狭窄的空间；把…藏入；收藏
data.enText: to put sth into a small space, especially to hide it or keep it safe or comfortable

data.chText: 她把头发拢起来塞进帽子里。
data.enText: She tucked her hair (up) under her cap.

data.chText: 他盘着腿坐着。
data.enText: He sat with his legs tucked up under him.

data.chText: 那封信压在了一摞文件下面。
data.enText: The letter had been tucked under a pile of papers.

data.chText: 用…盖住；用…围紧；用…裹严
data.enText: to cover sb with sth so that they are warm and comfortable

data.chText: 她拿一条毯子把他的双腿裹好。
data.enText: She tucked a blanket around his legs.
tuck sth↔away

data.chText: 坐落在，位于（僻静的地方）
data.enText: to be located in a quiet place, where not many people go

data.chText: 这家店铺位于一条僻静的小巷。
data.enText: The shop is tucked away down a backstreet.

data.chText: 收藏起；使隐藏
data.enText: to hide sth somewhere or keep it in a safe place

data.chText: 她把他的来信收藏在抽屉里。
data.enText: She kept his letters tucked away in a drawer.

data.chText: 他们把几千英镑存在一个储蓄账户上。
data.enText: They have thousands of pounds tucked away in a savings account.

data.chText: 大吃；拼命吃；暴食
data.enText: to eat a lot of food
tuck sb in/up

data.chText: 把…的被子掖好
data.enText: to make sb feel comfortable in bed by pulling the covers up around them

data.chText: 我给孩子们盖好被子说晚安。
data.enText: I tucked the children in and said goodnight.
tuck in
tuck into sth

data.chText: 痛快地吃；狼吞虎咽地吃
data.enText: to eat a lot of food, especially when it is done quickly and with enthusiasm

data.chText: 来呀，大家痛痛快快地吃吧！
data.enText: Come on, tuck in everyone!

data.chText: 他在狼吞虎咽地吃一大盘通心粉。
data.enText: He was tucking into a huge plateful of pasta.

data.chText: （衣服或织物的）褶，打褶
data.enText: a fold that is sewn into a piece of clothing or cloth, either for decoration or to change the shape of it

data.chText: 去赘皮手术；减肥手术
data.enText: a medical operation in which skin and/or fat is removed to make sb look younger or thinner

data.chText: 食物，零食（尤指儿童在学校吃的糖果等）

trans: 给（孩子）掖好被子；给…盖好被子

tr: a straight sword with a narrow blade and two edges
a narrow flattened pleat or fold that is stitched in place
(sports) a bodily position adopted in some sports (such as diving or skiing) in which the knees are bent and the thighs are drawn close to the chest
draw together into folds or puckers

example: insert your ticket into the slot

tr: make a tuck or several folds in

value.def: If you tuck something somewhere, you put it there so that it is safe, comfortable, or neat.

example.ex: He tried to tuck his flapping shirt inside his trousers...
example.tran: 他设法把飘起的衬衫塞到裤子里。

example.ex: She found a rose tucked under the windscreen wiper of her car one morning.
example.tran: 一天清晨，她发现自己汽车的挡风玻璃雨刷下插着一支玫瑰。

value.def: Tuck is food that children eat as a snack at school.

example.ex: He stole a Mars bar from the school tuck shop.
example.tran: 他从学校小吃店偷了一条玛氏巧克力棒。

value.def: You can use tuck to refer to a form of plastic surgery which involves reducing the size of a part of someone's body.

example.ex: She'd undergone 13 operations, including a tummy tuck.
example.tran: 她已经做了 13 次手术，包括一次腹部瘦身整形手术。
